{"title":"Mis-prompt: Benchmarking Large Language Models for Proactive Error Handling","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"LLMs often face erroneous user prompts without receiving explicit error-handling instructions, yet existing evaluations focus on passive error handling and lack a comprehensive, proactive benchmark spanning detection, identification, correction, and guidance across diverse error types.","method":"Introduce Mis-prompt, a proactive error-handling benchmark with four tasks (Error Detection, Identification, Correction, Guidance) and a taxonomy covering 4 primary and 14 secondary error categories. Construct a 14,969-instance dataset of erroneous Wh-questions by (i) transforming FEVEROUS, CommonsenseQA, and ROCStories, and (ii) directly generating prompts with GPT-4o, enforcing clauses with erroneous information and a false-statement+question structure. Provide ground truths for all four tasks, de-duplicate with Sentence-BERT at cosine >0.85, and perform manual review with substantial agreement (Fleiss’ κ=0.78) yielding a 93.76% acceptance rate."},{"problem":"There is no standardized, scalable protocol to quantify LLMs’ proactive error-handling capability or to assess how training can improve it.","method":"Design an automated evaluation pipeline that uses GPT-4o as a judgment model with task-specific prompts and F1 scoring, validated by human assessment. Benchmark 13 LLMs under zero/1/3-shot, CoT, and LoRA-based SFT. Results show weak zero-shot performance (avg F1≈37.53%), with detection easiest and accurate correction/guidance weakest, and reveal that supervised fine-tuning on error-handling instances yields large gains (e.g., LLaMA-3.1-8B 35.15→81.77, Qwen-2.5-32B 43.24→89.55). Error-category analysis further shows strengths on factual errors and weaknesses on language errors and incomplete information."}]}
